1. Introduction¶

In the fast paced world of basketball, the performance of the players is often refined into quantifiable data, which then is scrutinized by teams and fans alike. This data is used to determine the skills and worth of a NBA player and team either to get players or learn more about the strenghts and weakensses of a team. This project takes a look at the player statistics from the 2022/2023 NBA regular season. We are focusing on the main three statistics: points, rebounds, and assists.

By looking at these statistics, this project aims to uncover some patterns and insights that can contribute to a deeper understanding of player performance and possibly even team success. Through the comprehensive data science pipeline of data collection, processing, exploratory analysis, and visualization, we look to provide that deeper understanding of player performance. Additionally this project uses modeling techniques to test some hypotheses and apply machine learning algorithms as well, aiming to predict points, assists, and rebounds of NBA players.

2. Data Curation¶

Source of Data: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/vivovinco/20222023-nba-player-stats-regular

This is the website where we acquired our data about the NBA. This data has all the player's game statistics in the NBA during the regular season. Some of the main statistics include

  • Player position
  • Player Team
  • Player Age
  • Player Points Per Game
  • Player Assists Per Game
  • Player Rebounds Per Game

Question 1: How Does Age Affect the 3 Major Player Statistics?¶

We want to answer how age affects PPG, APG, RPG. To test this we will make a scatterplot with these three catagories and we will find a line of best fit for each graph. Lastly we will find the Pearson's Correlation between the three scatter plots.

First we are creating a box plot of age to see how it is distributed. We want to make sure there aren't too many outliers in age.

We see that the there aren't to many outliers so we can continue to create a scatter plot.We have no need to remove any outliers or adjust our data.

For our Statistical Test we will find a line of best fit for each catagory and find the Pearson correlation to see how strong the correlation is.

In [7]:
# Create easier variables to work with
age = df['Age']
ppg = df['PTS']
apg = df['AST']
rpg = df['TRB']

ppgGraph.scatter(age, ppg, label='PPG', color='blue', marker='o')
# Make a line of best fit of 1 degree (Not repeating comments for sections later)
m, b = np.polyfit(age, ppg, 1)
# Plot the line also make it contrasting color and thicker to show up on graph
ppgGraph.plot(age, m * age + b, color='darkorange', linewidth=4)
ppgGraph.set_title('Age vs. PPG')

apgGraph.set_title('Age vs. APG')
apgGraph.set_xlabel('Age')
apgGraph.set_ylabel('Assists per Game')
apgGraph.legend()

    # Assuming 'C' is already used for centers and doesn't need to be replaced

We can see minor differences across these groups, with centers having most notably the fewest points and most rebounds, while the guards have the most points and assists and fewest rebounds.

We next run ANOVA tests, to see if there are position has a significant effect on PPG, APG, and RPG. ANOVA tests are most appropriate in this scenario, as we are comparing the mean of over 2 (3) groups.

Null Hypothesis 1: Position does not affect PPG. Alternate Hypothesis 1: Postion affects PPG.

Null Hypothesis 2: Position does not affect APG. Alternate Hypothesis 2: Postion affects APG.

Null Hypothesis 3: Position does not affect RPG. Alternate Hypothesis 3: Postion affects RPG.

Significance Level: 0.05

In [12]:
# We next run an ANOVA test
anova_pos_apg = f_oneway(df['AST'][df['Pos'] == 'C'], df['AST'][df['Pos'] == 'F'], df['AST'][df['Pos'] == 'G'])
anova_pos_rpg = f_oneway(df['TRB'][df['Pos'] == 'C'], df['TRB'][df['Pos'] == 'F'], df['TRB'][df['Pos'] == 'G'])
anova_pos_ppg = f_oneway(df['PTS'][df['Pos'] == 'C'], df['PTS'][df['Pos'] == 'F'], df['PTS'][df['Pos'] == 'G'])

# Printing the results
print("ANOVA results for Position vs APG:")
print("P-value:", anova_pos_apg.pvalue)
print()
print("ANOVA results for Postion vs RPG:")
print("P-value:", anova_pos_rpg.pvalue)
print()
print("ANOVA results for Position vs PPG:")
print("P-value:", anova_pos_ppg.pvalue)

ANOVA results for Position vs APG:
P-value: 9.40396245444161e-17

ANOVA results for Postion vs RPG:
P-value: 4.284116988772909e-31

ANOVA results for Position vs PPG:
P-value: 0.1910406413523737

We can tell from these ANOVA P-Values that we will reject null hypothesis 1 and null hypothesis 2, and that we will fail to reject null hypothesis 3. We have statistically significant evidence to believe that position has an effect on RPG and APG, but do not have statistically significant evidence to believe that position has an effect on PPG.

So we see a significant difference between one of the positions and APG

We also see a significant difference between one of the positions and RPG

CONCLUSION:

While our graph does not show major differences between PPG, APG, and RPG among different positions, we run ANOVA tests to further analyze these differences. Through these tests, we learn that position does have an effect on player RPG and APG. This could be the case, as it positively impacts how easy it is to get rebounds. Being closer to the backboard is an extremely large advantage when rebounding, and centers and forwards are generally taller.

A post hoc test with our 2 tests that gave us a significant value could also be worthwhile to find which positions differed from which.

This graph shows minor differences among the 3 major statistics across the two groups.

We now run T-Tests to further search for differences across these two groups. We choose to use a T-Test, as it is most appropriate for two independent samples where we do not know the population standard deviation.

Null Hypothesis 1: Mean PPG does not vary across playoff and non-playoff teams. Alternate Hypotheis 1: Mean PPG varies across playoff and non-playoff teams.

Null Hypothesis 2: Mean APG does not vary across playoff and non-playoff teams. Alternate Hypotheis 2: Mean APG varies across playoff and non-playoff teams.

Null Hypothesis 3: Mean RPG does not vary across playoff and non-playoff teams. Alternate Hypotheis 3: Mean RPG varies across playoff and non-playoff teams.

Significance Level: 0.05

In [16]:
# Create separate dataframes for playoff and non-playoff teams
playoff_teams = df[df['Playoff'] == 0]
non_playoff_teams = df[df['Playoff'] == 1]

# Conduct t-tests for each statistic
s1, p1 = stats.ttest_ind(playoff_teams['PTS'], non_playoff_teams['PTS'], equal_var=False)
s2, p2 = stats.ttest_ind(playoff_teams['AST'], non_playoff_teams['AST'], equal_var=False)
s3, p3 = stats.ttest_ind(playoff_teams['TRB'], non_playoff_teams['TRB'], equal_var=False)

# Display results
print("The p-value for the T-Test analyzing PPG across the two groups is:")
print(p1)
print("The p-value for the T-Test analyzing APG across the two groups is:")
print(p2)
print("The p-value for the T-Test analyzing RPG across the two groups is:")
print(p3)

The p-value for the T-Test analyzing PPG across the two groups is:
0.6020307820065602
The p-value for the T-Test analyzing APG across the two groups is:
0.5173456999028525
The p-value for the T-Test analyzing RPG across the two groups is:
0.7326400178665333

Because all p-values are above our sigificance level, we will fail to reject all null hypotheses. We do not have statistically significant evidence to believe that being on a playoff team results in different player statistics.

CONCLUSION:

Through our bar graph and T-tests, we can see that there are little to no differences across PPG, RPG, and APG for players on playoff and non-playoff teams. From this we can infer that making it to the playoffs isn't only about player performance, but also takes building a team with several players who can contribute, and who have chemistry. It is also important to note that all teams will have players who serve various roles in their team, meaning that each team will have its high, medium, and low scorers.

Data Exploration Takeaways¶

From our data exploration, we could see that age and team strength had little influence on points per game, rebounds per game, and assists per game. However, position played a role in predicting rebounds per game and assists per game, as shown by our ANOVA tests. Therefore, when constructing our ML models which predict RPG and APG, it will be wise to include this feature in our model. On the other hand, when creating our model for PPG, we will want to use the other features we have not looked at so far, as age, team strength, and position all had weak relationships with PPG.

3. Machine Learning & Data Visualization¶

Model Selection¶

Our goal for this project is to use existing data to predict the points per game (PPG), rebounds per game (RPG), and assists per game (APG) of NBA players. From our data exploration, we discovered how age and team strength had weak relationships with the variables of our three statistics (PPG, RPG, APG). However, we also discovered that position had strong relationships with RPG and APG. Since our goal is to predict all three statistics (rather than just RPG and APG), it was evident we needed an ML model which uses more features than just the ones we analyzed in our exploration.

We want to use multiple variables, which are a mix of continuous and categorical, to predict our outcome variables, which rules out traditional regression models. Our outcome variables (PPG, RPG, APG) also are continuous, ruling out many traditional classification models. However, special random forest regression models allow us to develop forests of decision trees which can use both categorical and continuous features and also, crucially, predict a continuous variable. These models also avoid overfitting, as we are not relying on just one tree for our model, but instead the combined results of many.

Therefore, we elected to use a random forest regression model for our ML model so we will be able to predict our players's NBA statistics.

Random Forest Regression Model¶

Now that our data is cleaned, we can move on and implement our random forest models! We are creating a random forest model for each of our 3 major statistics (PPG, RPG, and APG).

NOTE: For our random forest regression models, we will not be specifying a maximum depth. We do this because we want to make use of as many features as possible (and learn more about each feature's respective importance), and because our dataset is not extremely large, allowing us to ignore performance concerns.

For the following steps we will use the following imports:

  • from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
  • from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
  • from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
  • from sklearn.tree import plot_tree

The above imports are all in the Data Curation section.

PPG Model¶

We start by defining our features and target, and then splitting the data into our train and test sets. For our features, we include variables such as games played, games started, shooting percentages, fouls, blocks, turnovers, position, and team quality. However, we do not include shots made as that allows for direct calculation of PPG. We also do not include APG and RPG as a feature since we are also trying to predict those two variables.

In [18]:
# Define features and target
X_ppg = df[['Age', 'G', 'GS', 'MP', 'FG%', '3P%', '2P%', 'eFG%', 'FT%', 'STL', 'BLK', 'TOV', 'PF', 'Playoff', 'Pos_C', 'Pos_F', 'Pos_G']]
y_ppg = df['PTS']

# Split the data into train and test sets
X_train_ppg, X_test_ppg, y_train_ppg, y_test_ppg = train_test_split(X_ppg, y_ppg, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

We next fit our model.

In [19]:
rf_ppg = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
rf_ppg.fit(X_train_ppg, y_train_ppg)

Model Evaluation & Data Visualization¶

Now that we created our ML Models, we must evaluate them, and also show their results.

We will using the following Imports to help us evaluate our model and help visualize them.

  • from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
  • from sklearn.tree import plot_tree

PPG Model¶

We first determine the root mean squared error (RMSE) of our model

In [27]:
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test_ppg, predictions_ppg)
rmse = math.sqrt(mse)
print("The RMSE of our PPG Model is", rmse)

The RMSE of our PPG Model is 2.277935940069172

Our RMSE of 2.278 is not negligable but not large when considering player PPG. This value suggests that our model does relatively well when calculating PPG, but that there is still some room for improvement. Our RMSE not being incredibly close to 0 also gives hope that we avoided overfitting.

We next look at the R-Squared value of our model and plot the residuals to further analyze whether it is a good fit or not.

In [28]:
r_squared = rf_ppg.score(X_test_ppg, y_test_ppg)
print("The R-Squared value of our PPG Model is", r_squared)

residuals_ppg = y_test_ppg - predictions_ppg

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.scatter(y_test_ppg, residuals_ppg, label='Residuals')
plt.hlines(y=0, xmin=y_test_ppg.min(), xmax=y_test_ppg.max(), colors='red')
plt.xlabel('Observed Values')
plt.ylabel('Residuals')
plt.title('Residual Plot For PPG Model')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

The R-Squared value of our PPG Model is 0.8868399520789985

This value is fairly close to 1, further suggesting that we have a fairly strong model. The residual plot shows that residuals increase with points per game, indicating that our model still needs improvement.

We now want to know which features played a key role in the creation of our models, as after all, we want to know which features have an impact on PPG. To accomplish this, we analyze importances of each of the features we used.

Analysis of Models¶

Our points per game model featured a RMSE of 2.277 and an R^2 value of 0.887. From these values, we could tell that our model had its fair amount of successes, but that there was room for improvement. Further, we could see from our residual plot that our model's residuals increased when predicting larger points per game. Our assists per game and rebounds per game had worse R^2 values (0.822 and 0.788), and showed similar issues in the residual plot, where residuals increased when predicting larger values. Issues like this could have occurred for various reasons.

One possibility is that our models overfit our training data. We created random forest models in attempt to avoid overfitting (as decision trees are notorious for overfitting), but we did not create any depth limit. The lack of depth limits could have prompted overfitting, as models with no depth limit tend to face such issues.

We also could have simply picked an inadequate model. Linear regression models could have been used (with more tedious data encoding and deletion of some features). Unsupervised algorithms also could have possibly been used.

Lastly, there is also the simple chance that we did not have enough data to properly predict PPG, RPG, and APG. Some of the features we have did not seem like strong predictors for PPG, RPG, and APG in our data exploration, and the features that ended up playing a large role in our models do not seem like they would be enough to predict the major statistics alone. While the features we have would likely be enough to predict if someone had a high or low value for our statistics, there is a strong chance we lack the information necessary to determine specifically how high someone scored rather than if they scored a high value or low value.

4. Insights and Conclusions¶

Our goal of this project was to gain a better understanding of NBA player's points per game, rebounds per game, and assists per game by analyzing 2022-23 Season data.

When studying points per game, we determined the following: Through our exploration, we discovered that age, position, and team quality played little role in determining PPG. Our ML model's feature importances however gave us better insight on what plays a role in predicting PPG. The highest scoring players are usually the ones with the most minutes played, turnovers also play a role along with field goal percentage, but not nearly as much as playing more minutes. This makes sense, as more time on the court will give players more opportunities to score and fewer turnovers could result in more scoring oppportunities.

When studying rebounds per game, we determined the following: Our data exploration revealed that position showed some relationship with rebounds. The feature importances of our ML model revealed that games started plays the biggest role in predicting RPG, along with minutes played, fouls, and field goal percentage. Fouls predicting RPG makes sense since players that pick up fouls are oftne the ones near the basket and thus more likely to pick up rebounds. Games played and minutes played also understandably play a role in predicting RPG, as more time on the court likely will lead to a player having more rebounds. However, field goal percentage is a variable that seems unexpected for predicting RPG. Taller players sometimes have higher field goal percentages, as they are closer to the rim, which could explain how they rebound more, but we would then expect our position variable to also play a large role in predicting RPG, as that would reflect this as well.

When studying assists per game, we determined the following: Similar to RPG, our data exploration revealed that position plays a role in predicting assists per game. Our feature importances of our ML model revealed that turnovers have the largest impact on assist per game followed by minutes played and the position of the player. Players that pass more tend to also turn the ball over more, explaining why turnovers could have predicted APG well. Simlar to the above statistics, more minutes played gives more chances for a player to have more assists, explaining how that helps in predicting. It is also understandable how position helped in predicting APG, as guards tend to be better passers in the NBA.

Through our data exploration and ML model, we were able to gain a better understanding of what statistics play a role in predicting the three major player statistics (PPG, RPG, APG) in basketball. While we improved our understanding, our model showed room for improvements as well.

Our PPG, RPG, and APG models had R^2 values of 0.887, 0.822, and 0.788 respectively, indicating that the models did not have a super strong fit of the data. Each model's residual plot also revealed that the residuals increased when predicting larger values. In order to improve our model, we could look to fine tune the model itself, possibly by implementing a depth limit in order to prevent overfitting. It is also possible that another model would have better fit our data, such as linear regression or unsupvised models like K-Means Clustering. Another possibility is that we simply lacked enough data for models to make proper predictions.
